    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The yellowing leaves on the lower stems of your tomato plants, a classic case of \"gibbous growth\" - a common affliction in the garden, where the lower leaves are left to wither and die, while the upper ones continue to thrive. It's a bit like a goblin's lair, where the lower levels are neglected and left to decay, while the upper levels remain well-lit and well-fed.\n\nAs for the cause, it's likely due to a lack of light or water reaching the lower leaves. Tomatoes need a balanced diet of water, nutrients, and sunlight to grow, and if the lower leaves are not receiving enough of these essentials, they'll start to turn yellow and drop off. It's a bit like a goblin's favorite snack - a tasty morsel that's been left to rot in the dark.\n\nTo fix the soil, you'll want to give your tomatoes a good soaking, making sure the entire plant is watered thoroughly. Then, add some organic matter like compost or manure to the soil to give it a boost of nutrients. You can also try pruning the lower leaves to allow more sunlight to reach the upper ones, and to encourage healthy growth. It's a",
      "source": "target",
